‚ú®SOURDOUGH POPOVERS‚ú®

This recipe is from my book! So LIGHT & AIRY and you‚Äôll LOVE the crispy, exterior shell!! The secret is THIN warm/room temp. batter, super hot preheated oven, and not opening the oven door! Just don‚Äôt. Keep it shut. You‚Äôll get mile-high results every time. Plus, the batter comes together in 5 minutes or less. Popover Recipe üëáüèº

Ingredients:
* 1 1/4 cups (300 ml) milk, whole or 2%
* 2 tbsp (28 g) unsalted butter, cubed
* 3 large eggs, at room temperature
* 1/2 cup (120 g) sourdough starter discard (or active sourdough starter)
* 1 tbsp Dijon mustard
* 1 tbsp finely chopped parsley
* 1/4 tsp garlic powder
* 1/4 tsp fine sea salt
* Freshly ground black pepper
* 1 cup (120 g) all purpose flour
* Cooking spray, for coating the pan

Method:
1. Preheat the oven to 450 F (230 C) for 30 minutes. Place a 6-cup non-stick popover pan inside to heat up.
2. In a small saucepan (or microwave), gently warm the milk and butter.
3. Whisk eggs, sourdough starter, mustard, parsley, garlic powder, salt and a few turns of freshly ground black pepper in a large bowl. 
4. Slowly pour the warm milk mixture into the egg mixture while whisking continuously.¬†
5. Add the flour, and continue to whisk until the batter becomes thin, frothy and lump free. The batter should be warm to the touch- this is KEY for light and airy popovers.
6. Remove the hot popover pan from the oven. Generously coat the inside and surface of the pan with cooking spray.
7. Pour/ladle the batter into the pan, filling each cup about 2/3- 3/4 full. 
8. Place pan into the oven. Reduce the heat to 400 F (200 C). Bake for 35-40 minutes. The popovers will be beautifully risen and deep golden brown when ready.
9. Serve piping hot!!

Most beginners think sourdough is complicated.
It isn‚Äôt when you follow a clear process & keep practicing üëåüèº

Here are my 5 steps that never fail, no matter how new you are to baking sourdough bread, you can do this!

‚úÖ 1. Use an active starter
Make sure your sourdough starter is bubbly and doubled before you mix.
Pro Tip: Feed it the night before if your kitchen is cool. It‚Äôs ready when it smells sweet and slightly tangy.

‚úÖ 2. Rest your dough after mixing
Mix starter, flour, water, and salt until no dry bits remain. Let it rest 45 minutes.
Pro Tip: This rest makes the dough stronger and easier to stretch later, which helps it rise higher in the oven.

‚úÖ 3. Stretch and fold three times
Every 30 minutes, lift and fold the dough.
Pro Tip: This replaces kneading. You‚Äôll feel it tighten each round, which means gluten is forming.

‚úÖ 4. Chill overnight for better flavor
Shape your dough, cover it, and refrigerate overnight.
Pro Tip: Cold proofing builds a deeper flavor and makes the dough easier to score in the morning.

‚úÖ 5. Bake cold and hot
Bake the dough straight from the fridge in a 475¬∞F (245¬∞C) preheated Dutch oven.
Pro Tip: The cold dough hits the hot pot and traps steam, which helps your sourdough spring and open beautifully.

When I first started baking sourdough bread, I remember cutting into my loaf and thinking‚Ä¶

‚ÄúWhere‚Äôs the crunch?‚Äù

It looked fine but the crust was soft, pale, and honestly, a little disappointing.

Here‚Äôs what I eventually learned: that perfect, crackly sourdough crust doesn‚Äôt come from fancy gear. It comes from getting three simple things right.

1. Add steam.
Steam helps your sourdough rise before the crust hardens. I use the double pan method or pour water into a hot tray to create steam. It completely changed my bread.

2. Don‚Äôt underbake.
Once the lid‚Äôs off, lower the oven to 400¬∞F and bake until the crust turns a deep golden brown‚Äîabout 20 to 25 minutes. It should smell rich and toasty.

3. Cool it uncovered.
Always cool your sourdough on a rack. If it sits on a pan or is covered, the trapped steam will soften the crust. Let it rest for at least an hour. It‚Äôs worth it.

If your sourdough crust has been soft or pale, try these three tips. They took my bread from flat and chewy to golden and crisp.

Recipe below for this olive oil sourdough üí• #ad Adding a high-quality extra virgin olive oil, like @californiaoliveranch, makes for an incredibly supple, luxurious dough‚Äîand an even better final loaf. Flavor! Texture! More flavor! I love eating this style of sourdough bread plain, but it‚Äôs also incredible when sliced thick, toasted, drizzled with @CaliforniaOliveRanch‚Äôs Reserve Miller‚Äôs Blend Extra Virgin Olive Oil to really go all out with a robust drizzle, and finished with a flaky sea salt. Try it and tell me otherwise üôÇ

Keep in mind this is a very highly hydrated dough, so hold back Water 2 and add it in very slowly at the end of mixing, once the dough has been strengthened (bassinage technique).

Makes four loaves, halve it all for two.

 

Levain:

138g type 85 flour (or can mix 35% whole wheat and 65% white flour)

138g water

69g ripe sourdough starter

 

Main Dough:

1104g medium protein white flour suitable for bread
598g type 85 flour (high extraction), or you can use 35% whole wheat, 65% white flour)
92g @californiaoliveranch 100% California Extra Virgin Olive Oil
33g fine sea salt
1151g water 1
276g water 2 (use to adjust dough consistency)
345g ripe sourdough levain

Method:
1. Mix Levain ingredients and keep warm for 5 hr
2. An hour before the levain is ripe, add the flour and water 1 to a mixing bowl and mix until no dry bits. Let rest for 1 hour.
3. Add levain, mix on speed 1 for 3 minutes, rest 10 minutes, then add salt and Water 2 as needed. Mix until smooth, 4 min on speed 2. Add the OO at the end while mixing. 
4. Bulk ferment for 3.5 hours (it‚Äôs been cooler here, so longer as needed). Three sets of stretches and folds at 30-min intervals.
5. Shape and proof in the refrigerator overnight.
7. Preheat oven to 450¬∞F (230¬∞C), bake 20 minutes with steam, then 35 min without.

For this focaccia I‚Äôm using the good stuff: @californiaoliveranch 100% California Extra Virgin Olive Oil, not only in the dough, but also on top, and again after baking. For the potatoes, I like to slice them to 1/16 inch on a mandolin (or flex those knife skills) and then into a brine for at least a few hours to maximize their flavor. Before topping the focaccia, drain them and dry with paper towels, and kind of tuck them into the dough in spots (see the Reel) so they get crispy.

Sourdough focaccia recipe with brined potatoes and herbs. Makes two 10‚Äù focaccia.

Potato brine:
1 or 2 Yukon gold (or any yellow) potatoes, sliced into 1/16‚Äù slices
1 liter of water
1 teaspoon fine sea salt
¬†
Dough:
520g medium protein white flour (‚Äúall-purpose‚Äù flour)
385g high-protein white flour (‚ÄúBread‚Äù flour)
19g @calfironiaoliveranch Extra Virgin Olive Oil
17g fine sea salt
588g Water 1
96g Water 2
173g ripe sourdough starter, liquid
¬†
Method
1. Slice the potatoes, place in brine and then fridge for a few hours.
2. Mix: Add the flour, water 1, and levain to a stand mixer, mix for 5min until smooth. Let rest 10min.
3. Add salt, a splash of Water 2, and mix for another 5 minutes until the dough comes together around hook. Stream in more water if the dough can handle it. Then, stream in the olive oil slowly and mix until smooth.
4. Transfer to a bulk fermentation container for 3 hours. Do three sets of stretches and folds at 30-min intervals.
5. Grease two 10‚Äù round pans with olive oil (or one large 13x18 cake pan). Divide the dough into pans and cover. Let proof for 3 to 4 hours at room temperature.
7. Drain potatoes and dry (see caption). Preheat oven to 450¬∞F (230¬∞C). Pour about 1 tablespoon of olive oil on top of the dough and dimple aggressively with wet fingers. Spread the brined and dried potoes on top, any fresh herbs (I like thyme or rosemary), and flaky sea salt.
8. Bake for 35min. Remove to a rack to cool for a min, remove from pan and let cool completely. Drizzle on more olive oil.

This high-hydration sourdough bread recipe is the first thing I make when I come home from travel. Intensely flavorful, open and light, and just the perfect balance between chewy, crispy, and tender.

Sourdough bread recipe (makes four 900g loaves, but divide all the ingredients in half to make just two):

Levain
138g high extraction type 85 flour
138g water
69g ripe sourdough starter

Main Dough
1013g whole wheat flour (Octane)
322g type 85 flour
368g medium protein white flour (Central Milling ABC Plus)
33g fine salt
1150g water 1
368g water 2
345g levain

[[Method]]
1. Mix Levain ingredients and keep warm for 5 hr
2. One hour before your levain is ready, add the flour and water 1 to a mixing bowl and mix until no dry bits. Let rest for 1 hour, covered.
3. Add levain, mix speed 1 for 3 minutes (or by hand for 5), rest 10 minutes, then add salt and Water 2 as needed (bassinage). Mix until smooth, 3-4 min on speed 2 in a mixer.
4. Bulk ferment for 3 hours. Three sets of stretches and folds at 30-min intervals.
5. Shape into a large batard or boule and place in a proofing basket dusted with white flour.
6. Proof in the refrigerator overnight.
7. Preheat oven to 450¬∞F (230¬∞C), bake 20 minutes with steam, then 40-50 minutes without. Internal temp should reach 204¬∞F (95¬∞C). Let cool completely before slicing.

My parents came to this very city from Honduras in the 80s. I was born in The Bronx. We are a hard working immigrant family. I don‚Äôt take for granted for one second the work my parents had to put in to this system to ensure that I became educated, learned English, and found the opportunity to thrive. But that didn‚Äôt come without my own drive, dedication, and endless work ethic. Being a first generation immigrant is no walk in the park. Growing up in Louisiana with black skin is not easy either. But the best part about living in the U.S. is that our dreams are here for the taking. The success stories can be built and they can be made if you just NEVER GIVE UP.  My mom got her accounting degree at 45, raising 4 kids, cleaning houses and going to school at night. I‚Äôll never forget those nights.

When to know if your dough is ready to shape: this was a huge obstacle I had faced a year ago, and I was determined to figure it out. Not until months later did I learn and discover that just because a recipe says it takes approx 2-4 hours to ferment doesn‚Äôt mean it will be done by then. Plus I was always so scared to overproof my dough so I would cut it short, not actually read my dough and look for the signs. I never knew that your dough visibly will show you if it‚Äôs ready or not. I only knew that if I went past that time frame the recipe indicated that my dough would over proof. 
Here are 3 things that helped me know when I should shape my dough and that your dough is perfectly proofed. 
#1 - Push your bulk fermentation about 30 mins - 1 hour more don‚Äôt be afraid to extend the time, trust me it does work so well. It may be longer but you‚Äôll know when u see all the signs. 
#2 - Once all the signs are visible (bubbles on top and around sides of dough, clean to touch, jiggly dough, doubled in size or close to, a clean dough dump. 
#3 - Having a preshape and final shape helps with dough. Plus I love this step of the process. Dividing and preshaping bread dough: Adds strength to the dough. Prepares the dough into a form for easier and more consistent final shaping. Creates a tighter, uniform surface on the dough.

Here are 3 things that helped me the most when I first started out baking sourdough. 
ü´∂üèª#1 üëâüèª Start simple, stay consistent.
Stick to ONE recipe ONE method
(‚ÄúMaster the basics before changing anything‚Äù). I found a recipe that worked for me just by watching others and using their recipes as guidance and over time it began to improve, I tweaked what I felt confident enough to do for me. When you‚Äôre just beginning it gets overwhelming-you don‚Äôt need 20 formulas- just one that you can practice until it feels natural.
ü´∂üèª#2 üëâüèª A visual cheat sheet for dough readiness. I practiced this over and over so many times till I felt confident enough to know my dough. I started to look for the signs - all of them:
	‚Ä¢	Smooth top/dome shape
	‚Ä¢	Puffy sides/and pulls nicely away from your bowl when u touch it 
	‚Ä¢	Jiggly bowl
	‚Ä¢	Light bubbles
Once you practice this step it does become alot easier to know when u are done bulk fermenting, patience is key here & trusting the process too. 
ü´∂üèª#3 üëâüèª Don‚Äôt compare your loaf to someone else‚Äôs year 3. Give yourself room to learn. Your loaf will tell its own story. Everyone‚Äôs dough behaves differently‚Ä¶ and everyone‚Äôs journey starts in a different place.
What you‚Äôre seeing online is often someone‚Äôs year 3, 4, or 5 not their first few tries. Your job right now isn‚Äôt to match their results - it‚Äôs to learn your dough, build confidence, and enjoy the process.

I‚Äôve been baking this beautiful sourdough bread style for nearly 12 years, and I‚Äôve shared pictures and thoughts for more than 8 years of that time. But I‚Äôve struggled to post about baking sourdough in 2025, and I‚Äôll outline a few of the reasons below:

1) The expectations of an Instagram page have evolved beyond my time and capabilities, for sure. Posting pictures was delightful and low-stress‚ÄîI take them anyway, so why not share? Creating Reels requires a level of commitment I can‚Äôt make (and also a level of skill I don‚Äôt have, lol). Y‚Äôall, I‚Äôm a teacher, and that‚Äôs where my heart and my time commitment lie. Also, algorithmic social media is doing a lot of damage to our social fabric! But I won‚Äôt go down that road tonight‚Ä¶

2) Sourdough baking has, to a certain extent, been appropriated by folks who want to ‚Äòrepeal the 20th century.‚Äô This happened so quickly that it truly caught me off guard, and I haven‚Äôt been able to collect my thoughts about it beyond this: Sourdough baking should be a respite for people who work 50-hour weeks and need to decompress, people who want to build a skill that will nourish their entire community beyond their nuclear family, kids who want to explore their creativity, retirees who want to build skills, and yes, people who take care of their homes each day. Sourdough baking is for everyone in a complicated and loving society. 

3) Let‚Äôs be really real: It‚Äôs tough to post bread pictures when the fragile fabric of our democracy is under daily assault. Knives and scissors to it, when it was already thin. We‚Äôre all going to have to fight harder for it.

AND YET, I believe that sourdough bread still matters a great deal. It‚Äôs the most delicious and sustaining food. It nourishes family, friends, students, neighbors. It‚Äôs humbling, too‚ÄîI‚Äôve baked thousands of loaves, and I still bake weird and unsatisfactory ones all the time! It can ebb and flow as a pursuit, but it‚Äôs lifelong.

I actually have some new thoughts on unorthodox sourdough process that I hope to share in the coming weeks and months! But I need to find the right time and context. Until then, peace. And POWER.

The lack of gluten is challenging, but the flavor makes the experimentation worth it!

I‚Äôve been thinking a lot lately about the subject of my pinned post. What does baking sourdough at home mean in this moment? I hope it remains a symbol of nourishment, expansiveness, and community care, rather than one of reaction and retreat to an imagined past on the prairie.

Shouts out to @maurizio for opening my eyes to the beauty of a ‚Äòfrico crust‚Äô: the cheesy edges of a pan bread created by pushing shredded cheese deep into the edge crevices. The most interesting part is that bagged cheese works best for this crispy purpose! I threw in a whole roundup of pics I never got around to sharing in recent weeks and months. 

Students continue to remind me of the possibility of a loving and capacious vision of society and polity and world. I don‚Äôt think of this vision as an endpoint‚ÄîI think that it takes and will continue to take empathy, openness, commitment, and work, in perpetuity. Being able to bake sourdough less frequently than I used to actually brings into clearer focus how lovely it is, as a respite and ritual to recharge for the work.

As promised in my previous post, I want to share a few tips for creating breadscape gardens like these, followed by the formula I used for this dough. First, the tips:

1) As I mentioned previously, the best base I‚Äôve ever found for the surface of the dough is a thin layer of simple basil pesto. The flavor is wonderful and complements the vegetables, and it also helps them stick to the surface of the dough. 
2) Don‚Äôt just lay the vegetables on top of the dough. Nestle them in there. Play around with pushing some of them in at different depths‚Äîthis adds interest to the loaves once baked!
3) Spray your loaves with a light layer of vegetable or olive oil before baking. This is magical, because it prevents burning, minimizes shriveling, AND seems to help maintain the vibrancy of the color. This combined with the pesto on the surface of the dough envelopes the vegetables with a protective layer, and makes the bread more delicious too.

The veggies I used are detailed in the previous post. On to the formula. (I can‚Äôt promise I‚Äôll use exactly the same formula next time, because I rarely do the same thing twice, but I can promise this one works!)

400g all-purpose flour
50g spelt flour (if you‚Äôve got in on hand‚Äîif not, then use what you‚Äôve got!)
250g water
100g 100% hydration sourdough starter
30g melted butter
20g olive oil
50g honey
10g salt

Mix it all together. Let it sit for an hour or so. Give it a few folds. Let it sit more! Fold again. Do that about four times over the course of 3-4 hours. Then let it rise between 50 and 100%. 

I allow loaves to proof for about 90 minutes before topping and baking, which I do at 425f. 

Happy baking, peace n‚Äô power to you, more to come.

This base has olive oil, a touch of honey, and a bit of rye. Toppings included basil pesto, red onion, scallions, carrots, cherry tomatoes, bell pepper, peas, poppy seeds, sesame seeds, dried garlic, and Swiss Alps seasoning. 

I have a few tips for creating these loaves! The first is to use a very thin layer of pesto as a base. It doesn‚Äôt interfere with the color, it adds moisture and flavor, and it helps the vegetables stick to the surface of the dough. I‚Äôll share a few more tips with the post-bake photos. Baking soda! 

Baking soda works for sourdough discard recipes because sourdough contains the acids needed to create a reaction. Some notes:
‚Ä¢A more acidic starter means a stronger reaction, but usually the flour in an acidic starter is more broken down leading to a less-fluffy, but more tender, result.
‚Ä¢Too much baking soda will leave a metallic taste ü§¢
‚Ä¢Baking soda and baking powder are *almost* the same. Baking powder contains the acids needed for the reaction, while baking soda doesn‚Äôt. If there‚Äôs enough acid in your discard, you don‚Äôt need baking powder. 1 tsp soda = 1 tbsp powder

Not all discard recipes use baking soda to add fluff. This is just one method out of several.

I love whole grains for their flavor and nutrients, but I love to bake 50/50 with them (50% whole grains, 50% white flour) for balance. This ratio gives me lots of whole grain flavor while still being able to produce an airy loaf.

-Absorb more water
-Struggle to retain air
-Be slightly more sour (depending on how, exactly, fermentation rolls)

Cramique Recipe (Sweet Belgian Brioche):
Ingredients:
‚Ä¢ 250g bread flour
‚Ä¢ 150g whole milk (50g warm + 100g room temp)
‚Ä¢ 50g sweet stiff starter
‚Ä¢ 50g sugar (rubbed w/ lemon zest & vanilla)
‚Ä¢ 5g salt
‚Ä¢ 1 whole egg + 1 yolk
‚Ä¢ 50g softened butter
‚Ä¢ 75g pearl sugar

Instructions:
1Ô∏è‚É£ Mix & Hydrate: Combine room-temp milk, eggs, sugar (pre-rubbed with zest & vanilla), and flour in a stand mixer. Mix into a shaggy dough. Let rest 15-20 min to hydrate.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Develop the Dough: Add the sweet stiff starter, knead for a few minutes. Dissolve salt in warm milk, add to dough, and knead until incorporated.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Butter Enrichment: Slowly incorporate softened butter, kneading until smooth, elastic, and slightly sticky.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Bulk Ferment: Cover and let the dough rise at room temp for 2-4 hours, or overnight in the fridge for deeper flavor.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Shaping & Proofing: Gently fold in pearl sugar, shape into a loaf or rolls, and place in a greased pan. Let proof 1-2 hours until puffy.

6Ô∏è‚É£ Bake: Brush with egg wash, sprinkle extra pearl sugar, and bake at 375¬∞F (190¬∞C) for 20-30 min until deep golden brown.
